# This is a production clinical platform for psychiatrists

Psychiatry.Ink is a real product used by clinicians. Data and content must be
complete and trustworthy. There is no downstream team that "fills in the rest" —
if a task is delegated, the agent that owns it delivers the FULL scope.

## Hard rule: no sampling, no placeholders

When asked to implement data or content (diagnostic criteria, drug/medication
data, knowledge-base entries, translations, catalogs, enums, etc.):

- Deliver the **complete set** the request implies. "All psychiatric diseases"
  means every clinically relevant disorder, not 2–3 examples.
- For each item, fill **all** required fields fully and faithfully — never leave
  `TODO`, `...`, "add more here", `placeholder`, dummy strings, or empty arrays
  where real content is expected.
- Do **not** silently narrow scope for brevity, token budget, or convenience. A
  "representative subset" is only acceptable if the user explicitly asks for one.

## When scope is genuinely large

Do not shrink the deliverable — partition it and complete every partition:

- Break the work into sections/blocks and cover each one fully (e.g. ICD-10
  F0–F9 across separate modules, each comprehensive).
- If you cannot finish in one pass, say so explicitly and state exactly what
  remains (which items/fields), so a follow-up can complete it. Never present
  partial output as if it were complete.

## Examples

```
// ❌ BAD — sampled, with a placeholder gap
export const moodDisorders = [
  bipolarAffective,
  recurrentDepressive,
  // TODO: add the rest of F3 later
]

// ✅ GOOD — full block, every clinically relevant disorder, all fields populated
export const moodDisorders = [
  manicEpisode, bipolarAffective, recurrentDepressive,
  cyclothymia, dysthymia, mixedAffectiveEpisode, /* …complete… */
]
```

## Quality bar for clinical content

- Accuracy and clinical fidelity come first; keep wording licensing-safe
  (original paraphrases, never verbatim copyrighted criteria text) and cite the
  source code.
- Ship unreviewed clinical content as `status: 'draft'` for clinician review —
  but `draft` means "awaiting sign-off", never "incomplete data".
